---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import FoundationPager from '../../components/FoundationPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'The ContextOps lifecycle';
const description =
  'Build, distribute, maintain, update, measure. Five stages. Every command maps to one.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="foundation">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    ContextOps is to context what DevOps is to code: a versioned, governed
    lifecycle that prevents drift between what the agent thinks is true and
    what the code actually does.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Build</h2>
  <p>
    Generate the initial context files by scanning the repo, not by guessing.
    Detect the stack from manifests, test commands from scripts, the dominant
    style from recent commits.
  </p>
  <p>Commands: <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a>, <a href={url('commands/document/')}><code>document</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>2. Distribute</h2>
  <p>
    Same rules, in the format each harness expects. Single source of truth,
    thin pointer files per harness.
  </p>
  <p>Commands: <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a>, <a href={url('commands/scope/')}><code>scope</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>3. Maintain</h2>
  <p>
    Pre-commit hooks and CI checks that validate context files when the code
    they describe changes. If <code>package.json</code> changes and
    <code>AGENTS.md</code> still names the old framework, fail the commit.
    Without this stage, context rots.
  </p>
  <p>Commands: <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>, <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>4. Update</h2>
  <p>
    Context evolves through delta updates, not full rewrites. New conventions
    added with a date. Deprecated ones marked, not deleted, with the reason.
    Rewrites lose the why; the why is the valuable part.
  </p>
  <p>Commands: <a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a>, <a href={url('commands/document/')}><code>document</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>5. Measure</h2>
  <p>
    Track how often the agent's output passes the project's own checks
    without modification. Low conformity means the context is failing to
    communicate.
  </p>
  <p>Command: <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>What to do with this</h2>
  <p>
    Build → Distribute → wire Maintain. Skipping Maintain is the most common
    failure: teams build beautiful context files and never check whether the
    agent actually follows them. <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>
    closes that loop.
  </p>

  <FoundationPager slug="contextops-lifecycle" />
</Doc>
